msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `vale` using Mason"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `vale` from within NvChad using Mason, will keep the package up-to-date with just a few extra steps. Running Mason periodically from within `nvim` will show you if there are updates that need to be installed and allow you to update them from there. This includes `vale` once it is installed. Let us start by running `nvim` to pull up an empty file and then get into the command mode by using <kbd>SHIFT</kbd>+<kbd>:</kbd>+Mason, which should show an interface similar to this one:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:26
msgid "![vale_mason](images/vale_mason.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rather than looking at the entire list of packages, let us use menu item 4 to limit the listing to linters. Press <kbd>4</kbd> and scroll down in the list until you find `vale` and with your cursor on that line, press <kbd>i</kbd> to install. Your listing should now show `vale` installed:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:30
msgid "![vale_mason_installed](images/vale_mason_installed.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring and initializing `vale`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:34
msgid ""
"There are two methods you can use to configure `vale`. You can pick your "
"favorite from the two options below. One will have you create the "
"configuration files from within the path of the `vale` binary, then move "
"them to your home folder, and the other will have you create the "
"configuration files directly in your home folder. They work equally well. "
"The second option has fewer manual steps, but requires the long path to the "
"`vale` binary."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "    If you want to hide your \"styles\" folder (below), modify the contents of the `.vale.ini` slightly during creation by changing the \"StylesPath\" option from \"styles\" to something hidden such as \".styles\" or \".vale_styles.\" Example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:42
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    StylesPath = .vale_styles\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:44
msgid ""
"Just having `vale` installed is not enough. You need a couple of additional "
"items. First, you need a `.vale.ini` file that will live in the root of your "
"home folder. Next, you will need to generate the \"styles\" directory using "
"`vale sync`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing from within the path of the `vale` Binary"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:48
msgid ""
"If you are in the path of the `vale` binary here: `~/.local/share/nvim/mason/"
"packages/vale/` you can simply create the `.vale.ini` file here, generate "
"the \"styles\" directory, and then move both of them to your home root `~/`. "
"Creating the `.vale.ini` file is easy using the configuration utility from "
"[the `vale.sh` website](https://vale.sh/generator). Here, choose \"Red Hat "
"Documentation Style Guide\" for the base style and \"alex\" for the "
"supplementary style. Using 'alex' is optional, but helps you catch and fix "
"gendered, polarizing, or race-related words, etc., which is important. If "
"you choose those options, your screen should look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:50
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:77
msgid "![vale_ini_nvchad](images/vale_ini_nvchad.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:52
msgid ""
"Simply copy the contents at the bottom, create the `.vale.ini` file with "
"your favorite editor, and paste what you copied in."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:54
msgid ""
"You need to create the \"styles\" folder. Do this by running the `vale` "
"binary with the `sync` command. Again, if you are doing this from the `~/."
"local/share/nvim/mason/packages/vale/` directory, just do:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "./vale sync\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:60
msgid "This will show the following when done:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:62
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:85
msgid "![vale_sync](images/vale_sync.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:64
msgid ""
"Copy the `.vale.ini` and the `styles` folder to the root of your home folder:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:65
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"cp .vale.ini ~/\n"
"cp -rf styles ~/\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing from your home directory"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:73
msgid ""
"If you prefer not to have to copy the files and just want to create them in "
"your home directory, you can use this command from `~/`:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:75
msgid ""
"First, create the `.vale.ini` in your home folder using [the `vale.sh` "
"website](https://vale.sh/generator). Again, choose \"Red Hat Documentation "
"Style Guide\" for your base style and \"alex\" for the supplementary style. "
"Then copy the contents into the `.vale.ini` file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:79
msgid ""
"Next, run the `vale sync` command. Since you are in your home directory, you "
"will need the entire path to the binary:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "~/.local/share/nvim/mason/packages/vale/vale sync\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/nvchad/vale_nvchad.md:87
msgid ""
"In this case, there is no need to copy the files as they will be created in "
"your home directory root."
msgstr ""

